With the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
Inventory Committee to prepare a Physical Inventory Plan pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006 and conduct a complete physical count, annually for PPE and semestrally for inventories. Also, reconcile the results of the count with the accounting records and submit the complete RPCPPE and RPCI to the Audit Team in accordance with Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume 1;
Municipal Accountant to (i) determine the estimated useful life of Work/Zoo Animals account as well as the Agricultural and Forestry Equipment account amounting to P403,629.92 which was abandoned by ARYA Cooperative and provide an allowance for depreciation thereof; and (ii) reclassify the amount of P281,190.24 to reflect the correct PPE balances in compliance with the Revised Chart of Accounts for LGUs;
Municipal Agriculturist and other offices to provide a system for proper monitoring of projects such as those transferred to Arya Cooperative and RSU and take appropriate actions for the recovery of the property upon breach of agreement; and
Accounting Office and Treasurer’s Office to maintain the prescribed property records and ensure that these records are regularly reconciled to achieve a timely and reliable financial report/statements.

With the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
Municipal Accountant to: (i) maintain subsidiary ledger for each fund transfer received to readily determine information on each fund and easily track its transactions and movements including related cash and payables; (ii) prepare FUR or ROD in compliance with the covering MOA or regulatory issuances, and submit the same to the Source Agency for their perusal and make sure that the Due to NGAs account is debited only upon project completion and full liquidation to source agency in compliance with Item 4.5 of COA Circular No. 94-013 and Annex A of COA Circular No. 2015-009; and (iii) disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the balance of Due to NGAs that have been implemented but not yet fully paid in order for readers and users to be informed of the status of implementation of projects funded by National Agencies;
Municipal Treasurer to return the unexpended funds totalling P88,538.51 to its respective source agencies if stipulated in the MOA/Trust Agreement and secure Official Receipt for the same in compliance with Items 4.9 and 5.5 of COA Circular No. 94-013.  Also, if the disposition as to the unspent balances and excess amounts of fund transfer are not stipulated in the MOA, Management must be guided by the provision of Section 3.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 which requires the submission of a letter by the IA to the SA for approval to transfer the unexpended balance to the GF;
BAC and the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking documents for the mentioned infrastructure projects and impose liquidated damages against the contractor for project no. 2; and
Municipal Engineer to ensure the accuracy of the STE in disclosing the revised expiry date of the contract or computation of slippage for the noted delays.

With the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
encourage coordination between the Municipal Budget Officer and newly – designated GAD Focal person to ensure conformance of identified PPAs and budget allocation in the approved Annual Budget and GPB;
instruct the GAD Focal Person to (i) strictly observe the schedule in GAD Planning and Budgeting as provided under Section 4 of PWC-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 2016-01; (ii) prepare and submit the GAD Accomplishment Report in accordance with Section 7.0 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01 and Section 4.1.C.8(5) of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01; (iii) refer to Section 3.0 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2016-01 in the attribution of the GAD Budget; and (iv) strictly observe the provision of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 to promote transparency, economy and efficiency in the procurement process;
through its GAD Focal Point System (GFPS), exhaust all available resources for the collection and processing of data requirements of the GAD Database to be able to comply with the recommendations of the DILG Provincial Office; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) coordinate with the GAD Focal Person in the preparation of the GAD AR; (ii) check the completeness and veracity of supporting documents prior to processing of claims in compliance with Section 474(b)(5) of P.D. No. 1445; and (iii) be guided with COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 which provides for the Revised Chart of Accounts for the LGUs in the recording of transactions.

With the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:
the MPDC and other concerned officials to ensure that the development projects to be funded out of the 20 percent DF are well-planned and procurement-and-implementation-ready to avoid spillovers in the succeeding year pursuant to Item 3.2.3 of DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1 dated November 4, 2020;
the BAC to provide to the Audit Team the noted documentary deficiencies in the procurement process and payment to suppliers and/or justification thereof;
the Municipal Accountant to see to it that all the necessary documentary requirements attached to the vouchers are accurate and complete before processing the claims;
the Municipal Engineer to disclose all ongoing government infrastructure projects in the quarterly Report of Government PPAs in compliance with Item 2 of COA Circular No. 2013-004; and
the MPDC to facilitate the adequate planning and budgeting of developmental projects and refrain from inputting lump sum or generic term appropriation as it will need separate approval from the sanggunian and provide copies of SB Resolution to the Audit Team for the PPAs funded out by the lump sum or generic term appropriation that had been identified by the seven barangays.

Based on the foregoing audit observations, we recommended that the BAC:

furnish the Audit Team with a copy of the Contract Agreement/Purchase Order and its attachments within five calendar days from execution/issuance thereof as required under Sections 3.1.1 and 3.2.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 23, 2009;






observe strictly the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and GPPB Circular No. 01-2020 dated April 6, 2020 to ensure adherence to the principles of transparency, competitiveness and public monitoring;






strengthen internal control over the evaluation of bids and post-qualification of bidders; 






prepare the required documents/reports with extra care to avoid errors which could mislead reader and users of the reports; and 






submit the lacking documents cited above to the Audit Team to comply with the requirements of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and address the deficiencies enumerated.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

remind the MDRRMO to ensure the preparation and inclusion of duly appropriated COVID-19 related PPAs in the LDRRMFIP of the Municipality in compliance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012;

require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer to prepare a monthly report on fund utilization and status of implementation of PPAs under the Bayanihan Grant in compliance with the provisions on Item 4.2 of Local Budget Circular No. 125 dated April 7, 2020;

henceforth, adhere with the posting and reporting requirements provided in Items 4.3 and 4.4 of Local Budget Circular No. 125 dated April 7, 2020 and furnish the Audit Team of the monthly reports and written notice to the oversight bodies;

render a written explanation or justification on the (i) grant of Special Risk Allowance (SRA) to the officials and employees in excess of the maximum allowable amount of SRA provided under LBC No. 2020-2 dated April 7, 2020; (ii) basis of computation of the COVID-19 Hazard Pay granted; (iii) non-implementation of the Municipality of the work from home arrangement and non-issuance of a written authority on allowing the Municipal frontliners and public health workers (PHWs) to physically report for work during ECQ as provided under Unnumbered Memoranda dated March 16, 2020 and April 7, 2020 and CSC Announcement No. 13, s. 2020 dated March 17, 2020; and (iv) procurement of fuel for the consumption of barangay personnel and BHERTs for the use of their private vehicles contrary with the provisions of Section 3.1.1.8 of COA Circular No. 96-004 dated April 19, 1996; and

require the Municipal Accountant to (i) account inventory items to their corresponding inventory accounts and record the corresponding expense only upon issuance/consumption thereof; (ii) review the regularity and completeness of supporting documents of disbursement vouchers before processing claims for payment; and (iii) adhere strictly with the fundamental principles in the financial transactions and operations of the government set forth under Section 4 of P.D. No. 1445.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor:

as Chairman of the MSWMB, designate a department and/or individual who will take the lead in the implementation and monitoring of the solid waste management programs and activities and require the immediate (i) submission of lacking documents of the Municipality’s 10-year SWM plan in compliance with the final evaluation and approval of the National Solid Waste Management Commission (NSWMC); and (ii) revision of the contents of the MSWMP consistent with the NSWM framework;

require the members of the MSWMB to exert effort in the performance of their duties and responsibilities and implementation of the MSWMP and prescribed policies of the Ecological Solid Waste Management Act of 2000 to achieve the objectives of the ESWM Act and ensure prompt delivery of basic services and facilities to the community in relation to solid waste management and environmental protection;

as soon as the budget allows, prioritize the creation of Municipal Environmental and Natural Resources Officer (MENRO) who shall lead in the implementation of solid waste management programs and activities and monitoring thereof; and

in coordination with the members of the MSWMB, fast track the processing of various requirements for the operation of a sanitary landfill in accordance with Sections 40 and 41 of R.A. No. 9003 the soonest possible time to avert adverse environmental consequences.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor/ Municipal Accountant:

Ensure the immediate liquidation of long outstanding and non-moving advances or cause for the withholding of salaries from officials and employees who are still in active service;

Strictly require officials and employees to liquidate their cash advances within the prescribed period pursuant to 5.1 of COA Circular No. 97-002; 

Ensure that no additional cash advances shall be granted to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance granted to him/her has been settled or a proper accounting thereof has been made pursuant to Item 4.1.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 and Section 89 of PD 1445; 	


Ascertain from the list if national employees with outstanding cash advances are still connected with the government and immediately send the bill/demand letter to concerned personnel. Make representation on this regard to the Head of the Agency concerned and its Accountant; and

Request for the write-off of long outstanding advances granted to officers and employees which remained non-moving for 10 years or more and where settlement/collectability could no longer be ascertained following the procedures under COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

